Yesterday I toke my pen and designed this.

Quite upset looking at the news and the return of war in Europe. 
Really behind the people's of Ukraine, no country should invade another one un provoked. I can't stop thinking about innocent life and the stability of the peaceful European alliance and safety of my own country. 

As an artist, there is only one way to express myself through my artwork. 
No war!

Feel free to use this image as you wish, my pen and art is my only weapon. Share it and let's stand for Ukraine.

National Bank of Ukraine opened a special account where everyone can send money to.

BENEFICIARY: National Bank of Ukraine
BENEFICIARY BIC: NBUA UA UX
BENEFICIARY ADDRESS: 9 Instytutska St, Kyiv, 01601, Ukraine
ACCOUNT NUMBER: 400807238
PURPOSE OF PAYMENT: for crediting account 47330992708

But many people do not know how to do that. 
I will show you on Chase Bank example how to do that step by step very easy.

Please find below a short guide how send wire transfer from your US bank account to Ukraine army:
1. You have to log in your account, go to Pay & transfers and choose Wires & Global, then press Add recipient 
2. Choose Ukraine in Bank Country, enter routing number NBUA UA UX, press Next. After that all info about the bank will appear automatically 
3. Enter account number 400807238 twice, choose Recipient - Business, Recipient Account Currency - US Dollars, then press Next
4. Enter ‚Äúfor crediting account‚Äù in Message to Recipient, group - Ungrouped, press Next 
5. Check everything and press Add Recipient 
6. Then press Schedule Wire 
7. Choose account which you are sending money from, enter amount and payment purpose, press Next and Authorize Wire in US dollars

The Ukrainian brand NCYZIP was supposed to be with the team at Paris Fashion Week right now, but didn't make it. The war has begun. 

Waking up at 5 a.m. from the sound of sirens is what our grandparents were most afraid of after World War II. At first there was fear, pain, loss, incomprehension. Through tears, fear and panic we pulled ourselves together and now our people, our army and our government are doing everything to make peace.

Part of our team is safe, part of the team is still on the run. Terrible things are happening. Grief, pain, fear, hatred, devastation - that's what we're feeling right now. The question "how are you, how is your family" has become equal to the phrase "I love you."

In Kiev, a rocket hit a house near our office.Our manufacture in Chernihiv was destroyed by a rocket attack, there are people who were injured. Now we have no time for fashion and no time for business. The brand exists only in our hearts. We help to defeat the invader with everything we can.

The main help now is to make sure that the whole world knows that there is a real war going on! Tell everyone about the war, show pictures, videos. Talk about the war.

There is a special account on the website of the National Bank of Ukraine to collect funds to support the Armed Forces of Ukraine.

üá∫üá¶I was born & raised in Kherson, Ukraine. I moved to the U.S. in 2013 with my mom at the age of 15, right before Russia illegally annexed Crimea in 2014, where I spent most of my childhood. Now, I feel very guilty‚Ä¶

‚Ä¶ guilty for not being in Ukraine with my grandparents, cousins, aunts, and uncles.
‚Ä¶ guilty because most people there are currently unable to live in safety.
‚Ä¶ guilty for having a refrigerator full of food while the majority of people in Kherson, Kyiv, Kharkiv, Mariupol, and other parts of my country are starving & there are now confirmed cases of people dying from dehydration.
‚Ä¶ guilty for not being able to help physically.
‚Ä¶ guilty enjoying a sunset while people are sitting in trenches, bomb shelters or wherever they can hide from Russian rockets and bullets.

Psychologists say that it is normal to feel guilty for being lucky to escape the horror, but‚Ä¶

I know that I have younger cousins who do not deserve to spend their childhood in the realities of warü•∫üíî

Like most of you, I have been watching the news in horror as the unprovoked invasion of the Ukraine by Russia continues. 

I spoke a little with my Ukrainian publisher, @vivat_book. Just a glance at their Instagram brings home how quickly things changed, and how impossible it is to imagine how their lives were upended. Photos of happy people holding up books give way to images of war.

Their offices are in the middle of Kharkiv. Employees have lost their homes to shelling in residential areas. People are dying. The person I spoke with described it as ‚Äúhell.‚Äù What she and everyone else there are going through is unfathomably terrible.

I discussed things with my international rights agents and we have frozen all contracts under negotiation and halted sales of future books (including renewals) in Russia. 

I am also going to be donating directly to Ukraine, at the place my publisher suggested:
 
https://bank.gov.ua/en/news/all/natsionalniy-bank-vidkriv-rahunok-dlya-gumanitarnoyi-dopomogi-ukrayintsyam-postrajdalim-vid-rosiyskoyi-agresiyi

One of the distressing things I learned was that the Ukrainian book community is unsure of how much of Putin‚Äôs propaganda is believed by the world ‚Äî stories about how Ukraine is responsible for killing its own people and destroying its own cities.

That‚Äôs an awful thought on top of everything else, and I wanted to post this to say I unequivocally stand with Ukraine and I‚Äôm sending you my love.

‚Äã‚ÄãMy name is Oksana and I'm a 26-year-old designer from Ukraine. I studied architectural design at Kharkiv University, a city that was bombed two weeks ago. I prepared this tattoo design to portray faith in life, humanity, and love for our country. Seeing the broken lives of people, our cities destroyed is so painful. 

The quote in the design is a part of the poem written by Ukrainian poet Taras Shevchenko in the 19th century. It means:

"Keep fighting - you are sure to win! God helps you in your fight! For fame and freedom march with you, And right is on your side!"

I fled from war and arrived in Italy, where I am right now.  We are incredibly grateful to everyone who helps us, grateful for every little step each of us does toward winning. I am proud of the people who are standing and continue to fight.

Tattoos remain my passion, and I want to continue to develop my skills in this direction. I am infinitely happy to be part of the CTD team and I'm very grateful for all the support! 

Thank you Oksana for the beautiful work you do for our clients every day.
